Setup Instructions
Create the project structure:

bash
mkdir calculator_app
cd calculator_app
mkdir backend frontend
Backend (C++):

Save the C++ files in the backend folder:

calculator.h

calculator.cpp

main.cpp

CMakeLists.txt

Frontend (Python):

Save the Python file in the frontend folder:

calculator_gui.py

3.2 Building and Running
Step 1: Build the C++ Backend

On Linux/Mac:

bash
cd backend
mkdir build
cd build
cmake ..
make
./bin/calculator_backend
On Windows (using MinGW or Visual Studio):

bash
cd backend
mkdir build
cd build
cmake -G "MinGW Makefiles" ..
make
./bin/calculator_backend.exe
Step 2: Run the Python GUI

In a separate terminal:

bash
cd frontend
python calculator_gui.py
3.3 Communication Protocol
The Python GUI and C++ backend communicate using a simple text-based protocol over TCP sockets:

Command Format:

text
COMMAND [PARAMETERS]
Example Commands:

ADD 5 3 - Add 5 and 3

SIN 30 - Calculate sine of 30 degrees

EVAL 2+3*4 - Evaluate expression

MADD 10 - Add 10 to memory

HISTORY - Get calculation history

Response Format:

text
STATUS|EXPRESSION|RESULT|ERROR_MESSAGE
Example Responses:

SUCCESS|5 + 3|8| - Success with result

ERROR|||Division by zero - Error occurred

3.4 Features of This Architecture
Separation of Concerns:

Python handles GUI and user interaction

C++ handles all calculations and logic

Each component can be developed independently

Cross-Platform:

Works on Windows, Linux, and macOS

Uses standard sockets for communication

Scalability:

Multiple GUI clients can connect to the backend

Backend can be extended with more features

Easy to add new operations

Performance:

C++ backend provides fast calculations

Python GUI provides responsive interface

Asynchronous communication

Extensibility:

Add new mathematical functions in C++

Customize GUI appearance in Python

Add database support for history

Implement graphing capabilities
